ingdom","Gunnolston, Nottinghamshire,England":"Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","South Wingfield, Derbyshire, England":"South Wingfield, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wingfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Winfield  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Winfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from Wingfield in Derbyshire, Bedfordshire, Suffolk, and Wiltshire. The Derbyshire placename probably derives from Old English <i>winn</i> ‘pasture, meadow’ + <i>feld</i> ‘open country’. The Bedfordshire placename may derive from Old English <i>wince</i> ‘nook, corner’ + <i>feld</i>. The Suffolk placename may derive from the Old English personal name <i>Wiga</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) or Old English <i>wīg</i> ‘idol’ + <i>feld</i>. The Wiltshire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wina</i> + Old English <i>feld</i>."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> 